    <!-- HOW THE WRITING SYSTEM FITS TOGETHER -->
    <section class="how-section" id="writing-systems">
        <div class="how-card">
            <h2>One Language, Four Writing Systems</h2>
            <p>Japanese is written with a mix of scripts. <strong>Kanji (漢字)</strong> are logographic characters that carry meaning, <strong>hiragana (ひらがな)</strong> is the curved kana syllabary used for native words and grammar, and <strong>katakana (カタカナ)</strong> is the angular kana syllabary used for loanwords, foreign names, and emphasis. <strong>Romaji (ローマ字)</strong> writes the same sounds in the Latin alphabet using Hepburn romanization, so learners can pronounce any word.</p>

            <p>Because all four systems can express the same sounds, real Japanese text constantly moves between them — furigana readings above kanji, katakana forms of borrowed words, and romaji in textbooks and passports. That is exactly what these converter tools automate: give them Japanese text in one script, and they return it in another.</p>

            <div class="reading-example">
                <div class="kanji-big" aria-hidden="true">語</div>
                <div class="readings">
                    <strong>Kanji:</strong> <span>日本語</span><br>
                    <strong>Hiragana:</strong> <span>にほんご</span><br>
                    <strong>Katakana:</strong> <span>ニホンゴ</span><br>
                    <strong>Romaji:</strong> <span>nihongo</span> — "Japanese language"
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>Use the <a href="/kanji-to-hiragana-converter.html">Kanji to Hiragana Converter</a> when you can see kanji but not read it — it adds hiragana readings, romaji, and word-by-word meanings. Use the <a href="/converter/hiragana-to-katakana">Hiragana to Katakana Converter</a> to switch between the two kana scripts in either direction. And to write your own English name in Japanese, the <a href="/">Japanese Name Translator</a> converts it into katakana, hiragana, kanji (ateji), and romaji.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

